    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a potent offensive outlook, anchored by **Yordan Alvarez** (84.61) and **Junior Caminero** (75.43), our two highest-scoring assets. **Yordan Alvarez** benefits from a favorable matchup against Emerson Hancock, with his elite xwOBA metrics and favorable lineup placement in the #2 spot driving his projection. Meanwhile, **Junior Caminero** faces the most exploitable arm on the slate in Luis Gil (5.74 xERA), allowing the Zebras to capitalize on his power upside despite a slight park penalty. **Christian Yelich** also surges into elite territory (74.33) against Jake Irvin, where his dynamic platoon advantage pushes him to a must-start status.\n\nAggressive baserunning remains our primary leverage point, evidenced by the decision to start **Hyeseong Kim** (61.92). While his #8 spot in the order is a drag, the match against Kumar Rocker\u2019s slow delivery gives **Hyeseong Kim** an inflated stolen base ceiling that exceeds the standard production of our bench options. The most difficult exclusion today was **Josh Smith**, who posted a competitive 53.82 score. While **Josh Smith** gained significant utility from his platoon advantage and stolen base potential against Tyler Glasnow, he ultimately couldn't displace the higher floor offered by **Caleb Durbin** (57.95) or the lineup-dependent value of **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (67.03), who receives a massive +14% boost from his platoon matchup.\n\nRisks remain, primarily due to the \"Lineup Pending\" status across the board, which forces us to rely on projected orders. We are tracking a negative wind factor for **Pete Crow-Armstrong** in his matchup against Mlodzinski, and **Chase Meidroth** (55.14) faces a stiff test against the low xERA of Kris Bubic. We are also benching **Victor Scott II** (35.39) despite his elite speed; his matchup against a high-tier arm like Connelly Early (2.34 xERA) in the bottom of the order creates a risk profile that does not justify a start given our current lineup density.",
